1
00:00:09,788 --> 00:00:14,478
Well, I already just alluded to
what we described.

2
00:00:15,657 --> 00:00:18,112
We hear this in story, remember:

3
00:00:18,112 --> 00:00:20,710
“There are no facts, 
just interpretations.”

4
00:00:20,710 --> 00:00:24,121
We hear stories,
we hear stories of great love

5
00:00:24,121 --> 00:00:28,451
and it resonates, 
it affects part of us.

6
00:00:28,744 --> 00:00:34,676
So, it means that 
we’re actually seeking

7
00:00:34,676 --> 00:00:37,461
to live in the subjective world.

8
00:00:37,461 --> 00:00:38,344
That’s what I’m saying.

9
00:00:38,344 --> 00:00:40,862
Actually, that’s what we want to do.

10
00:00:40,862 --> 00:00:43,152
Just like when someone
goes to a movie,

11
00:00:43,152 --> 00:00:45,921
they really like it if
—they’ll say—

12
00:00:45,921 --> 00:00:47,635
if you just forget yourself

13
00:00:47,635 --> 00:00:50,523
and live in that for two hours.

14
00:00:50,523 --> 00:00:55,393
So, we’re the only species
who really does that,

15
00:00:55,393 --> 00:00:57,441
or, to the extreme,
in human species.

16
00:00:57,441 --> 00:00:59,572
So, what it really points to is:

17
00:00:59,572 --> 00:01:02,500
we want to live
in the subjective world,

18
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:04,951
and we’re at present 
halfway between

19
00:01:04,951 --> 00:01:07,031
the objective
and the subjective world.

20
00:01:07,031 --> 00:01:09,128
In other words, if we’re sitting

21
00:01:09,128 --> 00:01:11,983
and looking at a master artwork

22
00:01:11,983 --> 00:01:16,538
in the Uffizi Museum in Florence,
by Leonardo,

23
00:01:16,538 --> 00:01:19,114
I can’t prove to someone that

24
00:01:19,114 --> 00:01:22,091
this is great art; it’s a masterwork.

25
00:01:22,091 --> 00:01:25,853
But, if that person’s willing to hear,

26
00:01:25,853 --> 00:01:28,000
to undergo some study,

27
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,216
then it’s possible
that they can come to

28
00:01:30,216 --> 00:01:33,290
the point of appreciating
the depth of beauty—

29
00:01:33,290 --> 00:01:35,787
the subjective aspect 
of what is there.

30
00:01:35,787 --> 00:01:39,368
We’re always seeking
subjective things.

31
00:01:39,368 --> 00:01:42,570
We’re attracted to hear a story,

32
00:01:42,570 --> 00:01:44,487
whether it’s true or not.

33
00:01:44,487 --> 00:01:46,461
As they say,

34
00:01:46,461 --> 00:01:48,425
“If you want to tell the truth,
write fiction”;

35
00:01:48,425 --> 00:01:50,842
“Art is a lie that tells the truth.”

36
00:01:50,842 --> 00:01:54,219
So, we’re not really concerned
about its objective aspect.

37
00:01:54,219 --> 00:01:56,873
When we look at
the beautiful Renoir painting

38
00:01:56,873 --> 00:01:58,886
of the flowers or whatever,

39
00:01:58,886 --> 00:02:00,740
they’re not real flowers.

40
00:02:00,740 --> 00:02:02,485
Maybe a real flower,

41
00:02:02,485 --> 00:02:05,071
upon close examination,
is more beautiful,

42
00:02:05,071 --> 00:02:08,963
but if an artist does
some sort of representation there,

43
00:02:08,963 --> 00:02:10,663
we’ll appreciate that.

44
00:02:10,663 --> 00:02:14,090
Well, no … We’re saying,
“Oh, but look, so you’re saying that

45
00:02:14,090 --> 00:02:16,036
this flesh and blood 
is not real?”

46
00:02:16,036 --> 00:02:17,360
No, I’m not saying that,

47
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:21,333
but what allows me
to feel this and see it?

48
00:02:21,333 --> 00:02:26,194
I’m seeing it through these eyes,
touching it …

49
00:02:26,194 --> 00:02:29,142
What’s the seat 
of this experience?

50
00:02:29,142 --> 00:02:30,839
Then we’ll go to the mind,

51
00:02:30,839 --> 00:02:35,288
and then, more refined
than the mind: intellect.

52
00:02:35,288 --> 00:02:37,495
Kṛṣṇa says in the Gītā that

53
00:02:37,495 --> 00:02:40,344
the soul’s located in
even a more subtle plane.

54
00:02:40,344 --> 00:02:43,064
So, the soul is the enabler

55
00:02:43,064 --> 00:02:48,002
who’s enabling us to navigate
the objective world

56
00:02:48,002 --> 00:02:50,926
and have a sensual experience.

